    //**jassid Classification **//


        Common Name: 	Jassids


       Scientific Name: Amrascadevastans (Dist.)


      Family:		Cicadellidae


      Order:		Hemiptera


    Pest Category: 	Sap feeder

    //** jassid Identification **//

      Egg: Eggs are curved, elongated and yellowish white in colour, and deeply embedded in the midribs of large veins on the undersurface of the leaves.


    Nymph: Nymphs are flattened, pale yellowish green with characteristic way of moving diagonally in relation to their body, seen on the lower surface of leaves during daytime.


    Adult: Adults are about 3.5 mm in length. They are elongate and wedge shaped with pale green body. Adults are very active with sideway movements but quick to fly.


    Pest attacks the crop during 1-50 days age and attack is severe during winter.

    //** jassid Symptoms of damage **//

  Both nymphs and adults suck the plant sap and introduce salivary toxins that impair photosynthesis in proportion to the amount of feeding.


     1st and 2nd  instar nymphs feed near bases of the leaf veins, later instars get distributed all over the leaves but feed chiefly on the under surface of leaves.


      The affected leaves curl downwards, turn yellowish, then brownish before drying and shedding.


   Severe incidence lead to stunting of young plants and results in “hopper burn” injury.


    //** jassid Life History **//


     The female inserts about 15 eggs inside leaf veins. The incubation period ranges from 4-11 days. The nymphal period occupies 7-21 days depending upon weather conditions. Eleven generations have been estimated to occur in a year. Nymphs moult five times. Average number of eggs laid by female is about 15 with a maximum of 29.


      Jassids survive on a variety of wild hosts during dry season. Populations of the jassids occur throughout the year.


    //** jassid Biological Control **//


     Inter-crop with cluster bean, cowpea or sorghum or soybean or black gram to encourage predators of sucking pests.


    Release predator Chrysoperla zastrouviearabica or Coccinella septempunctata or Syrphus / Scymnus sp. Conserve spiders Distinaalbida and ants like Camponotus sp.


     Neem oil 1.0% + Neem Seed Kernel Extract 5.0% + 0.05-0.1% detergent


             Azadirachtin 0.03% (300 ppm) Neem Oil Based WSP Containing


     Verticillium lecanii 10gms/lit of water, wherever good formulations are available from reliable manufacturers


     Metarhizium anisopliae @ 50g (2 X 108 CFU/gm) or Verticillium lacanni @ 50 g (2X 108 CFU/gm) in 10 liters of water



    //** jassid Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


    Sow the resistant varieties early.


    Do not use high doses of nitrogenous fertilizers.


    Grow cowpea/ onion/ soybean as an intercrop in cotton to reduce early stage pest. Use Okra as a trap crop.


     Adopt proper crop rotation. During summer deep ploughing to expose soil inhabitating insects.  Remove and destroy crop residues/alternate host plants


    Use yellow sticky traps.


    Hand picking and destruction of affected plant parts, stressed floral bodies,  resettled flowers


      Installation of bird perches: "T" shape wooden/bamboo sticks @ 50/ha should be erected for encouraging predatory birds.



    //** Jassid Chemical /control screen **//


