    //** Aphids Classification **//

        Common name : Aphids


       Scientific Name : Aphis gossypii Glover


      Family  : Aphididae


       Order : Homoptera


        Pest Category: Sap feeder

    //** Aphids Identification **//

      Egg: The eggs are yellow, but they soon become shiny black in colour.


     Nymph: Nymphs are small, yellowish, or brownish on the under surface of the leaves and on the terminal shoots and are mostly wingless.  The nymphal period averages about 7-9 days.


    Adult: Adults are mostly wingless and yellowish brown to black in colour, about 1.25 mm long with  pair of small upright backward-pointing tubes found on the dorsal side of the last segment of the bodies of aphids


 Aphids vary in size and colour depending on conditions. In cool conditions they are medium-sized and blackish green or green spotted with dark green. In hot conditions they are smaller and are very pale whitish yellow. Most commonly they are light green spotted with darker green.


    //** Aphids Symptoms of damage **//

   Leaf crumpling and downwards curling hindering photosynthetic capacity of the plant. Younger plants suffer more attack than older plants.


    Leaves appear shiny and sticky due to honey dew excreted by the insects.  Later, sooty molds grow on honey dew and leaves have a black coating.


     Aphid populations are seen at the terminal buds and also found below cotton leaves sucking nutrients from the plant


   Activity of ants are commonly but they are there to collect honeydew excreted by aphids, and may even hinder predation by other insects.


    //** Aphids Life History **//


    Aphids live in colonies.  In a day female aphid may give birth to 8-22 nymphs. Nymphal period lasts for 7-9 days and the adults live for 12-20 days. In all, the pest has 12-14 generations per year.


      The duration of the adult\'s reproductive period is about 15 days, and the post-reproductive period five days.
        The optimal temperature for reproduction is reported to be about 21 to 27 degrees celsius. The females produce a total of about 70 to 80 offspring at a rate of 4.3 per day.


     Aphids produce sugary excretion called ‘honey dew’ on which sooty mould grows. Ant activity is associated due to the honey excretion by aphids. Ants transmit aphids from plant to plant.


     Aphids have a large host range with varying durations of development and reproductive rate.


    Excessive nitrogenous fertilizer applications stimulate faster development of aphids.


    //** Aphids Biological Control **//


   Release predator Chrysoperla zastrouviearaabica or Coccinella septumpunctata or Syrphus / Scymnus sp.


    Encourage and conserve spiders Distinaalbida and ants like Camponotus sp.


     Metarhizium anisopliae @ 50g (2 X 108 CFU/gm) or  Verticillium lacanni @ 50 g (2X 108 CFU/gm) in 10 liters of water


      Soap solution may be used to reduce Aphid population.








    //** Aphids Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


     Avoid late sowing and excessive use of nitrogenous fertilizers.


    Destroy infested shoots during early stages and destruction of various insect stages and the affected plant parts.


   Handpicking and destruction of various insect stages and the affected plant parts.


Excessive and unnecessary use of insecticides should be avoided.


     Infested crops should be destroyed immediately after harvest to prevent excessive dispersal, and it may be possible to destroy









