    //** whitefly Classification **//


        Common name : Whiteflies


       Scientific Name :BemisiatabaciGenn.


      Family  : Aleyrodidae


       Order : Hemiptera


     Pest Category: Sap feeder


    //** whitefly Identification **//

      Egg: Eggs are yellowish white laid singly on the under surface of leaves.


     Nymph: Nymphs are yellowish and brownish. They are found in large numbers on underside of leaves.


    Adult: Adults are tiny and white in color. They have a yellow body dusted lightly with a white waxy powder. Females are 1.1-1.2 mm long; males are slightly smaller. Antennae of females are longer than males. Large numbers of adults are found in middle region of the plant.


    //** whitefly Symptoms of damage **//

    The nymphs and adults cause damage to cotton plants in two ways firstly by sucking the sap and secondly  Leaves become shiny with  excretion of honeydew and formation of  sooty mould  all the over surface of the leaf and lints of opened bolls resulting in process of blackening


     Leaves curl upwards and the plant vigour reduces.


      Indirect damage results from lint contamination with honeydew and associated fungi and through transmission of leaf curl virus disease. Late season severity affects the seed development and the lint quality.


    Insufficient chlorophyll spotsare develop on leaves and in severe cases the vein becomes translucent, thickened and in many cases it drops off prematurely.


    //** whitefly Life History **//


      The female whitefly lays the eggs singly on the under surface of leaves and mostly on the top and middle crop canopy. Each female is capable of laying about 120 eggs. The incubation period varies from 3-5 days during spring and summer, 5-17 during autumn and >30 days during winter.


      The nymphs after hatching fix themselves to the underside of the leaves and they moult thrice before pupation. The nymphal period varies from 9-14 days during summer, and 17-19 days during winter.


      The pupal period is 2-8 days. The total life-cycle range from 14 to 107 days depending upon the weather conditions. There are about 12 overlapping generations in a year and the pest also reproduces parthenogenetically at times. Whiteflies have extremely wide host range.


     The period of activity of whiteflies lasts from the emergence of seedling to the full grown crop.



    //** whitefly Biological Control **//


     Naturally occurring biological control in the field is reported to have been effective to the extent of 65%.  Encourage activities of parasitiods like Encarsia shafeei or Eretmocerus spp., smundus.


      Release predators Chrysoperlazastrouviearabica@ 2 larvae/plant in early stage of the plant and 4 larvae/plant in later stage.


      Release Cheilomenes sexmaculata @ 1.5 lakh adults/ha at random on crop canopy. Other predators such as  Melochilus sexmaculatus or Coccinella septempunctata or Brumus sp. or Scymnus sp are also controls the infestation of whitefly


        Neem oil 1.0% + Neem Seed Kernel Extract 5.0% + 0.05-0.1% detergent


      Botanicals and biopesticides: Sprays based on Neem oil, castor oil, cotton seed oil, fish oil rosin soap etc., must be preferred to avoid disruption of naturally occurring biological control. If available, Lecanicillium lecanii may be used. Ensure that the sprays reach lower leaf surface to target nymphal stages.


        Metarhizium anisopliae @ 50g (2 X 108 CFU/gm) or Verticillium lecanii 10gms/lit of water.


    //** whitefly Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


      Promote Desi cotton varieties: Majority of Desi cotton varieties, species Gossypium arboreum are resistant to the whiteflies and immune to the cotton leaf curl virus (CLCuV). Desi cotton may be preferred in regions which are highly prone to cotton leaf curl virus disease (CLCuD) .


     Cultivate medium duration (160-180 days) Bt-hybrids for north India which escape from whiteflies infestation especially when sown before 15th may in North Zone.


    Judicious use of urea: Avoid excessive urea during vegetative phase of the crop. Excessive urea especially before square initiation makes the crop vulnerable to sap-sucking insects especially whiteflies and leaf hoppers.


Barrier crops: Grow two rows of sorghum or pearl-millet or maize as border around cotton fields.


        Avoid late sowing and adopt crop rotation with crop which is not the host of white fly.


During the initial phase of whitefly infestation use ‘yellow sticky traps’ at the canopy height in field to determine economic threshold levels and ‘vacuum suction traps’ for control.


     Remove and destroy crop residues after last picking.



    //** Whitefly Chemical /control screen **//


ACETAMIPRID 20% SP 

BUPROFEZIN 25% SC 

CHLORPYRIFOS 20% EC 

CHLORPYRIFOS 50% + CYPERMETHRIN 5%EC 

