    //** Pink Bollworm Classification **//


        Common Name    : Pink Bollworm


        Scientific Name:    Pectinophora gossypiella    Saund.


      Family                              : Gelechiidae


       Order                                  :  Lepidoptera


       Pest Category     :  Borer


    //** Pink Bollworm Identification **//

       Egg: Eggs are very small and pearl white in colour, smooth, oval in shape measuring approximately 0.5 mm long, 0.25 mm wide. Eggs are laid singly or in groups of 4-5 on the underside of tender parts of the plant (shoots, flower buds, leaves and green bolls).


      Larva: In early stage the larva is white and in later stage change to pink in colour. The larvae have dark brown head.


     Initial stage of pupae is light brown in colour and gradually become dark brown during later stage. Pupa measures up to 7 mm in length.



      Adult: The adult moth is greyish brown in colour with black spot on the forewings and the hind wings are silvery grey. Moths emerge from pupae in the evening time and hiding in soil debris or cracks during night time.



    //** Pink Bollworm Symptoms of damage **//


      If larva attacks the early buds of less than 10 days old, shedding of buds occurs and larva dies. But in older buds, larva can complete development.


      Infestation of larva in flower bud spins webbing that prevents proper flower opening leading to “rosetted-flower” is a  typical of pink bollworm attack.


    Ten to twenty days old cotton bolls are attacked from under bracteoles with small exit holes. Larvae feed on the developing seeds. While in younger bolls entire content may be destroyed, in older bolls development could be completed on three to four seeds.  There may be complete infestation of pink bollworm on bolls but need not be any shedding of boll.


    Stained lint around feeding areas resulting in bad quality kapas is seen in open bolls. Improper boll opening with damaged seed are obvious.


     Early in the season, infested squares continue growing and producing blooms. These infested blooms may have the petals tied together with silken threads, commonly termed "rosetted." The rosetted flowers do not open normally.



    //** Pink Bollworm Life History **//


       Early in the season, eggs are laid in stalk of the leaf or reproductive structure, the underside of young leaves, on buds or flowers. Once the bolls are 15 days old, the bolls are favoured sites for egg lay.  Eggs normally hatch in 4 to 5 days


     The larvae are white but turn pink as they age.  At hatching, the larvae have a dark head, but as they mature, the head becomes yellowish-brown in color.  They enter squares or bolls very soon after hatching from the eggs. As they feed in squares or bolls they grow to a length of about ¾ inch.  Larvae will feed for 10 to 14 days before pupating.  Larvae usually will leave the fruit and pupate in the soil, requiring about 8 days transforming into an adult.


   During the period of suspended development in an insect, the larvae often spin up in the lint of an open boll and if still active in ginnery, will spin up on bales of lint, bags of seed or in cracks and crevices. Moths emerging from the hibernating larvae are long lived with females and males alive for 56 and 20 days, respectively. Pink bollworm generally occurs at 90 days after sowing and beyond.



    //** Pink Bollworm Biological Control **//


   Release of egg parasitoids Trichogramma chilonis or Bracon elechidae or Elasmus johnstoni or pupal parasitoid Microbraconlefroyi controls the pink bollworm population.


Encourage the activities of predators Chrysoperla zastrouviearabica Scymnus sp. or Triphles tantilus or Pyremotesventricosus (mite) or release them in the fields.


Apply bacterial formulations Btk. @1 kg/ha.


      Follow IPM / IRM strategies using neem based products, botanicals, biopesticides and biological-control especially during the first three months to conserve naturally occurring biological control and to avoid chemical insecticides as much as possible.






    //** Pink Bollworm Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


    Since most pink bollworm damage occurs late in the season, planting early and maturing varieties can help prevent late-season pink bollworm damage.


     While planning for the next season, drying of seeds under sun for 6-8 hours and sowing of acid delinted seeds are effective and economical to prevent the carry-over of pink bollworm to the next cotton season. Maintenance of host free during off-season is a must to ensure a pink boll worm free in the next season.


 Care must be taken to monitor the pink bollworm infestation on the crop. Keep pheromone traps that attract the male moths. If few male moths are found in the traps, keep 20 nos of traps per hectare, so that mating is disrupted and the population development is arrested.


  For light and marginal soils under rain-fed tracts to be planted at 90x30 cm. For black-cotton soils, medium-deep soils and/or irrigated conditions to be sown at 120x30 cm or 120x60 cm


     Pink bollworm goes into diapause at the last larval instar (4th instar) stage. Such larvae spin a loose silky cocoon and are present sometimes in the soil but mostly in crop residues such as in seeds, bolls and stalks. Therefore crop residual management is important to prevent infestation in the subsequent season.


    Deploy timely crop termination to maintain closed season. Clean up/destruction of cotton stubbles immediate to harvest, avoiding stacking of cotton stalks for fuel purpose over long periods and summer deep plouging to expose the pupae of the surviving larvae constitute post-harvest and off season cultural measures





    //** Pink Bollworm Economic Threshold Level **//


         One egg or larvae per plant


         Morethan one egg/larvae per plant


         Morethan 5-10% Infested fruiting bodies


        Morethan 10% Infested fruiting bodies


