    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Classification **//


        Common Name    :   Spotted and spiny bollworms


        Scientific Name:    Earias vittella Feb. Earias. insulana Bois


      Family                              : Noctuidae


       Order                                  :  Lepidoptera


       Pest Category     :  Borer


    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Identification **//

       Egg: Eggs are spherical in structure less than 0.5 mm diameter and bluish green in colour. Eggs are laid singly on most part of the cotton plant (flower buds, bolls, stalk of the leaves or reproductive structure); the favoured region being young shoots.


      Larva: Full grown larva is about 1.3-1.8 cm long, stout and spindle shaped bearing a number of long hairs on each segment. Larva is light brown, tinged with grey to green, pale along the mid dorsal line with dark spots at the base of middle part of the body


     Pupation is in a boat shaped tough silken cocoon that is dirty, white to brownish in colour. Pupae are found on plants or on fallen buds and bolls.



      Adult: Adult moths differ with species. In E. insulana, the head, the upper body, and forewing colour varies from silver green to straw yellow; the far edge of wing is of the same colour. There are three distinct dark cross lines on the wings. Green forms are common during summer, while yellow/brown forms occur toward the end of season. E. vittella, moths are quite distinctively creamy white or peach in colour with a central green wedge running from near to far edge of the forewing.



    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Symptoms of damage **//


     Larvae cause damage by boring into the growing shoots, buds, flowers and bolls.


     Feeding holes in squares and on bolls are seen with or without larvae however blocked by excrement.


    The attacked shoots weaken, become wilt and ultimately die, flare up of squares and their shedding, premature dropping or opening of the attacked bolls are common.


    Terminal shoot dry and wither away when the larvae bore into the pre-square plants.






    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Life History **//


The female moth deposits 2 or 3 eggs on bracts, leaf axils and veins on the under surface of the leaf. A female may lay up to 385 eggs and the incubation period is about 3 days.


    The larva becomes fully grown in 10-12 days. The pupal period is 7-10 days. The total life cycle ranges from 20-22 days.    

  Population build up is large during the effective boll development phase of crop causing damage to all fruiting bodies.


The continuous damage to developing bolls caused by E. vittella along with intermittent rains lead to boll rot and results in large number of premature bolls opening with partial damage.


Okra and bhendi are the host crops which transmit the pest from one to the next season.


Earias incidence commences from 3 weeks old crop and the damage to fruiting bodies occurs during 15-16 weeks old crop.   Earias incidences are high whenever H.armigera incidence is low to moderate.


    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Biological Control **//


   Release egg parasitoid Trichogramma chilonis, T. brasiliensis, and larval parasitoids Chelonus blackburni or Bracon brevicornis at 35 to 70 days controls the pest infestation.


Conserve and encourage the activity of the spiders Thomisus sp. and Neosiana sp.


Spray crop with neem oil 5ml/lit + 5% NSKE + detergent powder per litre water to kill residual larvae









    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


    Timely crop termination, destruction of cotton stalks and crop residues in the fields reduce the survival and food supply and shelter to the bollworms.


    Plough deeply to expose resting pupae. Pre-planting clean up measures including keep the fields, bunds and borders free of weeds hosts and  destruction of plant debris and trash before sowing to break the link for the pest between cotton and alternate host crops.


 Pheromone traps for the pest  that attract male moths @ 10/ha for monitoring the ETL and timing of spray


  Excessive use of systemic insecticides during early season for sucking pest management and excessive nitrogen application should be avoided.


     The mechanical removal and destruction of the affected shoots along with the larvae during the pre and early squaring crop stage curtails the population build up further in the season.








    //** Spotted bollworm and Spiny Bollworm Economic Threshold Level **//


         One egg or larvae per plant


         Morethan one egg/larvae per plant


         Morethan 5-10% Infested fruiting bodies


        Morethan 10% Infested fruiting bodies


