    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Classification **//


        Common Name    :   Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar


        Scientific Name:    Spodoptera litura Boisd


      Family                              : Noctuidae


       Order                                  :  Lepidoptera


       Pest Category     :  Sap/ Foliage feeder


    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Identification **//

       Egg:Leafworm lays egg in mass contains 300-350 eggs which are arranged in rows up to three layers and are covered by scales from the body of the females.


      Larva: Larva or caterpillars are 25-35 mm long in size and pale green with dark markings initially which later turn dark brown in color with numerous transverse and longitudinal bands.


    Pupae are dark brown in colour. Normally pupation occurs in soil.



      Adult:Adult is stout with brownish forewings with paler lines along the veins, and pearly whitish hind wings.



    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Symptoms of damage **//


     The larvae feed on the under surface of the leaves and skeletonize them leaving only the midrib and veins in severe cases.They also feed on flowers, buds and squares causing considerable loss.


    Attacked leaves defoliate and shedding of squares with feeding holes occur when larvae are in large numbers









    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Life History **//


    Egg, larva and pupal periods are 3-4, 13-20 and 8-10 days respectively. Life cycle completed in 50-60 days.














    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Biological Control **//


   Release egg parasitoids Trichogramma sp. (1.5 lakh/ha) and larval parasitoids Chelonus blackburni or Telenomus remus or Bracon sp. To control the infestation of the pest


Release of predators Chrysoperla zastroviearabica @ 50,000 /ha.


Spray Spodoptera NPV @ 250 lit/ha.


   Spray crop with Neem oil 5ml/l +5% NSKE+ 1gm detergent powder per litre water to kill residual larvae.






    //** Leafworm or Tobacco caterpillar Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


    Plough deeply to expose the pupae and hiding larvae under the soil


   To monitor Spodoptera, pheromone lures can be fixed, however planting of few castor plants along the borders of the cotton fields serve as trap or indicator  plants for Spodoptera.


 Collection and destruction of egg masses and collection and destruction of larvae are feeding in groups,








