    //** Thrips Classification **//


        Common Name    :   Thrips


        Scientific Name:    Thrips tabaci Linde.


      Family                              : Thripidae


       Order                                  :  Thysanoptera


       Pest Category     :  Sap feeder


    //** Thrips Identification **//

       Egg:Eggs are smaller in size, kidney shaped laid in slits in leaf tissues.


      Larva: Nymphs are smaller in size and blackish in color and look like adults but wingless.


    Adult:Adults are straw or yellowish brown in colour and elongated measuring 1mm in length. Adults are slender and look like lice. Males are wingless and females have a long narrow strap like wings.



    //** Thrips Symptoms of damage **//


    Nymphs and adults tear the leaves and suck the sap from the upper and lower surfaces of leaves.


 The upper side of the affected leaves turn brown and the lower side becomes silvery white.


  Leaves become curled upwards, wrinkled and finally get dried. Rusty appearances in patches develop on under surface of leaves.



    //** Thrips Life History **//


    Eggs hatch in 5 days, nymphal and pupal period lasts for 5 and 4-6 days, respectively.


    The adults survive for 2-4 weeks. Life cycle of Thrips from egg to adult lasts for 13-19 days and they have about 15 overlapping generations per year including their development on wild plants.


  Thrips inhabit on leaves of cotton.  Thrips develops on the weeds during the off-season and migrate to cotton as soon as the seedlings emerge above ground and survive up to mid-season and colonise on bolls during the late season.


 Males are rare and the reproduction is parthenogenetic.



    //** Thrips Biological Control **//


      Encourage the activity of parasitoids Thripoctenusbriu, Triphlepstantilus and mite Campsid sp.


      Release Trichogramma chilonis 1.5 lakhs/ha. Release Chrysoperla zaastrouviearabica @ 2 larvae/plant in early stage of the plant and 4 larvae/plant in later stage or release Cheilomenes sexmaculata @ 1.5 lakh adults/ha at random on crop canopy.


         Metarhizium anisopliae @ 50g (2 X 108 CFU/gm) or Verticillium lacanni @ 50 g (2X 108 CFU/gm) in 10 liters of water


   Avoid spraying of any chemical insecticide during initial crop growth stage.



    //** Thrips Cultural and Mechanical Control **//


    Avoid late sowing of the crop.


 Grow cowpea/onion/soybean as an intercrop in cotton to reduce early stage pest infestation


 Deep ploughing in summer and keep weed free field and surroundings.


  Grow certified acid de-linted seeds of thrips tolerant varieties.



    //** Thrips Economic Threshold Level **//


         One egg or larvae per plant


         Morethan one egg/larvae per plant


         Morethan 5-10% Infested fruiting bodies


        Morethan 10% Infested fruiting bodies


